Helm Package Management
Prerequisites
Before starting this lab, you should have:

Basic understanding of Kubernetes concepts (pods, services, deployments)
Familiarity with YAML syntax
Command-line experience in Linux
A running Kubernetes cluster (minikube or kind)
kubectl installed and configured
Learning Objectives
By the end of this lab, you will be able to:

Understand Helm chart structure and components
Create a custom Helm chart from scratch
Deploy applications using Helm releases
Manage Helm releases (install, upgrade, rollback)
Use Helm templating features
Environment Setup
Step 1: Install Helm
# Download and install Helm
curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/helm/helm/main/scripts/get-helm-3 | bash

# Verify installation
helm version
Step 2: Start Kubernetes Cluster
# If using minikube
minikube start --driver=docker

# If using kind
kind create cluster --name helm-lab

# Verify cluster is running
kubectl cluster-info
kubectl get nodes
Step 3: Add Helm Repository (Optional)
# Add bitnami repository for reference
helm repo add bitnami https://charts.bitnami.com/bitnami
helm repo update
Task 1: Create a Custom Helm Chart
Step 1: Generate Chart Structure
# Create a new Helm chart
helm create mywebapp

# Explore the chart structure
cd mywebapp
tree .
Expected structure:

mywebapp/
├── Chart.yaml
├── values.yaml
├── charts/
└── templates/
    ├── deployment.yaml
    ├── service.yaml
    ├── ingress.yaml
    ├── _helpers.tpl
    └── tests/
Step 2: Modify Chart.yaml
Edit Chart.yaml to define your chart metadata:

apiVersion: v2
name: mywebapp
description: A simple web application Helm chart
type: application
version: 0.1.0
appVersion: "1.0"
maintainers:
  - name: Your Name
    email: your.email@example.com
Step 3: Configure values.yaml
Edit values.yaml with custom configuration:

replicaCount: 2

image:
  repository: nginx
  pullPolicy: IfNotPresent
  tag: "1.25-alpine"

service:
  type: ClusterIP
  port: 80

resources:
  limits:
    cpu: 100m
    memory: 128Mi
  requests:
    cpu: 50m
    memory: 64Mi

# TODO: Add custom configuration values
# - Environment variables
# - ConfigMap data
# - Additional labels
Step 4: Customize Deployment Template
Edit templates/deployment.yaml to add custom features:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: {{ include "mywebapp.fullname" . }}
  labels:
    {{- include "mywebapp.labels" . | nindent 4 }}
spec:
  replicas: {{ .Values.replicaCount }}
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      {{- include "mywebapp.selectorLabels" . | nindent 6 }}
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        {{- include "mywebapp.selectorLabels" . | nindent 8 }}
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: {{ .Chart.Name }}
        image: "{{ .Values.image.repository }}:{{ .Values.image.tag }}"
        imagePullPolicy: {{ .Values.image.pullPolicy }}
        ports:
        - name: http
          containerPort: 80
          protocol: TCP
        # TODO: Add environment variables from values
        # TODO: Add resource limits and requests
        # TODO: Add liveness and readiness probes
Step 5: Create a ConfigMap Template
Create templates/configmap.yaml:

apiVersion: v1
kind: ConfigMap
metadata:
  name: {{ include "mywebapp.fullname" . }}-config
  labels:
    {{- include "mywebapp.labels" . | nindent 4 }}
data:
  # TODO: Add configuration data
  # Example: app.conf, database connection strings, etc.
  index.html: |
    <!DOCTYPE html>
    <html>
    <head><title>{{ .Chart.Name }}</title></head>
    <body>
      <h1>Welcome to {{ .Chart.Name }}</h1>
      <p>Version: {{ .Chart.AppVersion }}</p>
    </body>
    </html>
Step 6: Validate Chart
# Lint the chart for errors
helm lint .

# Dry-run to see generated manifests
helm install mywebapp . --dry-run --debug

# Template the chart to view output
helm template mywebapp .
Task 2: Deploy and Manage Helm Releases
Step 1: Install the Release
# Install the chart
helm install mywebapp-release ./mywebapp

# List all releases
helm list

# Check deployment status
kubectl get all -l app.kubernetes.io/name=mywebapp
Step 2: Verify Deployment
# Get release status
helm status mywebapp-release

# View release values
helm get values mywebapp-release

# View all manifests
helm get manifest mywebapp-release

# Test the application
kubectl get pods
kubectl get svc

# Port-forward to access the service
kubectl port-forward svc/mywebapp-release 8080:80
# Access http://localhost:8080 in another terminal or browser
Step 3: Upgrade the Release
Modify values.yaml to change replica count:

replicaCount: 3
# Upgrade the release
helm upgrade mywebapp-release ./mywebapp

# Check revision history
helm history mywebapp-release

# Verify new replica count
kubectl get pods -l app.kubernetes.io/name=mywebapp
Step 4: Rollback Release
# Rollback to previous revision
helm rollback mywebapp-release 1

# Verify rollback
helm history mywebapp-release
kubectl get pods -l app.kubernetes.io/name=mywebapp
Step 5: Override Values During Install
# Create a custom values file
cat > custom-values.yaml <<EOF
replicaCount: 4
image:
  tag: "1.24-alpine"
service:
  type: NodePort
  port: 8080
EOF

# Install with custom values
helm install mywebapp-custom ./mywebapp -f custom-values.yaml

# Or use --set flag
helm install mywebapp-inline ./mywebapp --set replicaCount=5
Step 6: Package and Share Chart
# Package the chart
helm package ./mywebapp

# This creates mywebapp-0.1.0.tgz

# Install from package
helm install mywebapp-from-pkg ./mywebapp-0.1.0.tgz

# Generate index for chart repository (optional)
helm repo index .
Verification
Verify Chart Creation
# Check chart structure
ls -la mywebapp/

# Validate chart syntax
helm lint mywebapp/

# Expected output: No errors or warnings
Verify Deployment
# Check all releases
helm list --all-namespaces

# Verify pods are running
kubectl get pods -l app.kubernetes.io/name=mywebapp

# Check service endpoints
kubectl get svc -l app.kubernetes.io/name=mywebapp

# View release details
helm get all mywebapp-release
Verify Upgrade and Rollback
# Check revision history
helm history mywebapp-release

# Should show multiple revisions with status
Test Application Access
# Port-forward and test
kubectl port-forward svc/mywebapp-release 8080:80 &
curl http://localhost:8080

# Expected: HTML response from nginx
Troubleshooting
Common Issues
Chart validation fails:

# Check YAML syntax
helm lint mywebapp/ --debug

# Validate templates
helm template mywebapp mywebapp/ --debug
Release installation fails:

# Check detailed error
helm install mywebapp-release ./mywebapp --debug

# View Kubernetes events
kubectl get events --sort-by='.lastTimestamp'
Pods not starting:

# Check pod logs
kubectl logs -l app.kubernetes.io/name=mywebapp

# Describe pod for events
kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
Template rendering issues:

# Test template with specific values
helm template mywebapp ./mywebapp --set replicaCount=3 --debug
Cleanup
# Uninstall all releases
helm uninstall mywebapp-release
helm uninstall mywebapp-custom
helm uninstall mywebapp-inline
helm uninstall mywebapp-from-pkg

# Verify cleanup
helm list
kubectl get all

# Stop Kubernetes cluster (if needed)
minikube stop
# or
kind delete cluster --name helm-lab
Conclusion
In this lab, you have:

Created a custom Helm chart with proper structure and templates
Configured chart metadata and default values
Deployed applications using Helm releases
Managed release lifecycle (install, upgrade, rollback)
Used Helm templating to create flexible, reusable charts
Packaged charts for distribution
Helm simplifies Kubernetes application deployment by providing templating, versioning, and release management. These skills are essential for managing complex applications in production Kubernetes environments. You can now create reusable charts for your applications and manage their lifecycle efficiently.

